  "What is a 'trigonometric equation'?": "",
  "An equation containing trigonometric functions that is true only for certain values of the variable": "",
  "An equation that can only be solved graphically": "",
  "An identity that holds for all values of the variable": "",
  "Any equation involving angles": "",
  "A trigonometric equation contains trig functions and is satisfied only by specific values of the variable, unlike identities which are true for all values in the domain.": "",
  "What does the term 'general solution' mean when solving trigonometric equations?": "",
  "The set of all solutions including those found by adding full period multiples to each principal solution": "",
  "The approximate decimal value of the solution": "",
  "The solution that works for the largest range of angles": "",
  "The solution found by graphing": "",
  "The general solution accounts for the periodic nature of trig functions by adding integer multiples of the period to each solution found in one cycle.": "",
  "What is a 'reference angle'?": "",
  "The supplement of the given angle": "",
  "The angle measured from the positive y-axis": "",
  "Any angle between 0° and 360°": "",
  "The acute angle formed between the terminal side of the given angle and the x-axis": "",
  "A reference angle is the positive acute angle between the terminal side of an angle and the nearest part of the x-axis. It is always between 0° and 90°.": "",
  "What does 'extraneous solution' mean in the context of solving trigonometric equations?": "",
  "A solution obtained during the solving process that does not satisfy the original equation": "",
  "A complex-number solution": "",
  "A solution that satisfies the original equation": "",
  "A solution outside the interval [0, 2π)": "",
  "An extraneous solution is introduced by algebraic steps (like squaring both sides) and does not satisfy the original equation. Always check solutions in the original equation.": "",
  "What does it mean to 'isolate the trigonometric function' when solving a trig equation?": "",
  "To substitute a numerical value for the trig function": "",
  "To remove the trigonometric function from the equation": "",
  "To convert the equation to degrees": "",
  "To use algebraic operations to get the trig function alone on one side of the equation": "",
  "Isolating the trig function means rearranging the equation so a single trig expression (like sin x or cos x) is alone on one side, making it possible to find angle values.": "",
  "What is meant by 'principal solution' of a trigonometric equation?": "",
  "The solution found using the unit circle only": "",
  "The largest solution in a given interval": "",
  "The only solution to the equation": "",
  "The solutions found within one standard period of the function, typically [0, 2π) or [0°, 360°)": "",
  "Principal solutions are the solutions within one complete cycle of the trig function, usually [0, 2π). All other solutions are found by adding period multiples.": "",
  "What does 'factoring' mean in the context of solving trigonometric equations?": "",
  "Replacing the trig function with its Taylor series": "",
  "Rewriting the equation as a product of simpler expressions set equal to zero and solving each factor": "",
  "Graphing the equation to find x-intercepts": "",
  "Dividing both sides by the trig function": "",
  "Factoring rewrites a trig equation as a product equal to zero, so each factor can be set to zero and solved independently. This parallels factoring polynomial equations.": "",
  "What does 'quadratic form' mean for a trigonometric equation?": "",
  "An equation involving four different trig functions": "",
  "An equation that can only be solved by completing the square": "",
  "A trig equation structured like a quadratic (au² + bu + c = 0) where u is a trig function": "",
  "An equation with four solutions": "",
  "A trig equation in quadratic form looks like a sin²x + b sin x + c = 0 (or with cos, tan, etc.). It can be solved using factoring or the quadratic formula with a substitution like u = sin x.": "",
  "What does 'inverse trigonometric function' mean when solving equations?": "",
  "The negative of a trigonometric function": "",
  "A function that returns the angle whose trig value equals a given number": "",
  "A function that reverses the period of a trig function": "",
  "The reciprocal of a trigonometric function": "",
  "Inverse trig functions (like sin⁻¹, cos⁻¹, tan⁻¹) return the angle for a given ratio. For example, sin⁻¹(1/2) = π/6, giving a principal value angle.": "",
  "What does 'restricted domain' mean for inverse trigonometric functions?": "",
  "The domain excluding negative angles": "",
  "The domain where the original trig function is one-to-one, allowing an inverse to exist": "",
  "The set of angles where the function is undefined": "",
  "The interval where the function has no zeros": "",
  "Since trig functions are periodic and not one-to-one, their domains must be restricted to intervals where they are one-to-one so that inverse functions can be properly defined.": "",
